{
  "texts": [
    "The forms of description we apply to action belong to \"a type of description that would not exist if our question 'Why?' did not\" (ibid.)",
    "because they hook onto a distinctive kind of order in events.",
    "This order is not a matter of complexity only, both because equal complexity occurs in the merely causal order and because the question 'Why?'",
    "can be asked of quite simple movements.",
    "(Here, we might think of Fritz Heider and Mary-Ann Simmel's famous 'apparent behaviour' study [1944], replications of which have found subjects from very young ages onward attributing agency to simple square and triangular figures going through basic two-dimensional motions when these exhibit 'agent-like' features [Scholl & Tremoulet, 2000])."
  ]
}